Okay, based on what I just read, fiscal policy is indeed the use of government spending and tax policies to influence the economy. It's typically used to promote economic growth, achieve price stability, and ensure low unemployment.

So, during economic downturns, the government might implement expansionary fiscal policy, which involves increasing spending and/or cutting taxes to boost demand. Conversely, in times of economic boom, it might use contractionary fiscal policy by decreasing spending and/or raising taxes to cool down the economy and prevent inflation.

